# **Part 1 — Symmetric Cryptography (AES & DES)**  
**Tools Used:** CrypTool 2.1 (Kryptos Workflow Environment)

This section demonstrates how symmetric cryptography can be used to secure sensitive financial communication in an online banking environment. Using **CrypTool 2.1 with the Kryptos workflow system**, I implemented and compared two symmetric encryption algorithms: **AES** and **DES**. These methods form the foundation of confidentiality in secure digital banking systems.

---

## 🔐 **Encryption Methods Used**

### **AES (Advanced Encryption Standard)**  
AES was used as the **primary encryption method** in this project.

**Key characteristics:**
- Industry standard for secure online communication  
- Fast and efficient for high‑traffic banking systems  
- Supports 128/192/256‑bit keys  
- Strong resistance to brute‑force attacks  

AES encryption was performed using the **AES Encryption module inside Kryptos**.

---

### **DES (Data Encryption Standard)**  
DES was included for **comparison and legacy demonstration**.

**Key characteristics:**
- 56‑bit key (now considered insecure)  
- Useful for showing weaknesses of older encryption methods  
- Demonstrates why modern systems transitioned to AES  

DES encryption was performed using the **DES Encryption module inside Kryptos**.

---

## 🔑 **Key Generation**
All keys were generated **randomly** within Kryptos.

Random key generation ensures:
- Higher confidentiality  
- Lower predictability  
- Reduced risk of brute‑force or pattern‑based attacks  

---

## 🧪 **Hashing (Integrity Verification)**  
After encryption, I generated a **SHA‑256 hash** of the AES‑encrypted file.

This ensures:
- The encrypted message was not altered  
- Integrity can be verified by the receiver  
- Any modification triggers a mismatch  

Hashing was performed using the **SHA‑256 module inside Kryptos**.

---

## 🎯 **Purpose of Part 1**
Part 1 demonstrates:

- How symmetric encryption protects confidentiality  
- Why AES is preferred over DES in modern systems  
- How hashing ensures integrity  
- How encryption workflows are built using Kryptos in CrypTool 2.1  
- The foundation for Part 2 (asymmetric cryptography and digital signatures)  

This section establishes the core security mechanisms required for secure digital banking communication.

